{"Title": "The Balloon Experimental Twin Telescope for Infrared Interferometry (BETTII): Towards the first flight", "Year": 2016, "Source": "Proc SPIE Int Soc Opt Eng", "Volume": "9908", "Issue": null, "Art.No": null, "PageStart": null, "PageEnd": null, "CitedBy": 6, "DOI": "10.1117/12.2231918", "Link": "https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&scp=85007162482&origin=inward", "Abstract": "\u00a9 2016 SPIE.The Balloon Experimental Twin Telescope for Infrared Interferometry (BETTII) is a balloon-borne, far-infrared direct detection interferometer with a baseline of 8 m and two collectors of 50 cm. It is designed to study galactic clustered star formation by providing spatially-resolved spectroscopy of nearby star clusters. It is being assembled and tested at NASA Goddard Space Flight Center for a first flight in Fall 2016. We report on recent progress concerning the pointing control system and discuss the overall status of the project as it gets ready for its commissioning flight.", "AuthorKeywords": ["Balloon", "BETTII", "Far-infrared", "Interferometry", "Star formation"], "IndexKeywords": ["BETTII", "Direct detection", "Far infrared", "Infrared interferometry", "NASA Goddard Space Flight Center", "Pointing control system", "Spatially resolved spectroscopy", "Star formations"], "DocumentType": "Conference Proceeding", "PublicationStage": null, "OpenAccess": 2, "EID": "2-s2.0-85007162482", "SubjectAreas": [["Electronic, Optical and Magnetic Materials", "MATE", "2504"], ["Condensed Matter Physics", "PHYS", "3104"], ["Computer Science Applications", "COMP", "1706"], ["Applied Mathematics", "MATH", "2604"], ["Electrical and Electronic Engineering", "ENGI", "2208"]], "AuthorData": {"36931135500": {"Name": "Rizzo M.", "AuthorID": "36931135500", "AffiliationID": "60020304", "AffiliationName": "University of Maryland"}, "56287922100": {"Name": "Dhabal A.", "AuthorID": "56287922100", "AffiliationID": "60020304", "AffiliationName": "University of Maryland"},